segments.text: Yeah, well, to respond to that question, I don't think I labored on it.
I don't think it was in any particularly anomalous position.
I know that Islin really didn't understand or particularly value theoretical work.
I think some of the activity that I did during that period, like some of the field programs I tried to carry out, were in response to trying to please him.
But he was very suspicious of any kind of theoretical work at all.
I guess that maybe Walter's recollection of the times or something.
Maybe sometimes I felt a little bit hemmed in and prevented by the one-man structure of the institution that we had at that time.
Felt a little bit hemmed in and restricted in things that I could do.
Maybe thought, you know, I didn't have right access to the ship time or wasn't sufficiently appreciated or didn't get enough support or something like that.
I think, I think people can think those things.
I don't think it was very serious and I think, I think I probably did feel that way with Islam more than with Admiral Smith, who I think was very supportive.
But it was really, really often the trouble is not, the trouble is, is that
is developing a program clearly enough and specifically enough so that other people can understand it and can then begin to help support you to do it.
If you're struggling around in a kind of mental fog yourself,
And you don't get very much support on the outside.
That's really not the other people's fault, it seems to me.
Well, you may think so.
It's more your own limitation.
Basically, it seems to me that everything that one could conceive of that was reasonably decent and communicable eventually
eventually happens, maybe not, maybe not right away.
I think Gislin didn't support me very much in the Bermuda work.
I think that was a bad period for me, 53, 54.
And, but he probably had some pretty good reasons, can't argue against.
It would be interesting to know what the size of the early grants were in the first three years when I was at Harvard.
They probably were something like $50,000 a year or something like that, I suspect.
because I think I was probably, I wasn't paying part of the salary, but I think it was probably, it must have been something in that order.
What prompted you to move to Harvard?
Oh, temptation.
It was a very foolish thing to do, I think.
I think perhaps the, I, when I was, when I, I enjoyed my time at Yale very much.
I was there some seven years.
I liked the academic life there very much.
And although when I came to Woods Hole, I found Woods Hole a very nice place to be for the whole 16 years that I was there, it seemed to me there was sort of something missing.
There's a narrowness to a purely scientific institution that you notice if you have been in a place where before you could talk to lawyers or historians.
It's a very distinct process.
And so when I got this chance to go to Harvard, I really didn't really want to do it very much, but then I eventually did do it.
And of course, it's a very big university, and the place, the laboratory where my offices were, were completely immersed in engineering and physics.
In fact, the club is very big, and it would take half a lifetime to develop contacts with the historians and artists and so forth.
any kind of a fuzz play.
So it's kind of an impossible thing to recover some kind of an experience of that kind, I think, at least in the art of fuzz.
It might not be Cambridge England or something of that sort.
I think that was part of the reason
I think probably a large, large, large fraction of the region.
Also, I'd had, I'd had some nice contacts with some of the people there, George Carrier in particular was a very successful, I guess I shared the supervision of

of Alan Robertson's PhD thesis, which was a, mine was a pretty nice one, and so I suddenly got the idea that there were going to be some interesting students and people to talk to about how to work with, and professionally.
So that's what I, that's what I did.
I think it probably in the long run was kind of a mistake because I think it moved me too far away from work at sea and contact with ships and so forth.
I mean, if you compare my career to someone else's who's been single-mindedly devoted to working at sea,
Like some of the people in Wetzel, or like Swallow, for example, in England.
It's conspicuous and different.
It must have been 5% or 10% of the time that they are doing the work at sea.
It might have been that way anyway, but I think going to Harvard and MIT was a sure way to end up that way.
Did you go to sea often?

Not a great deal, but I mean, I could see that the, certainly more than now, and I think, I think that might have been a, that was a dividing point, a fork in the road, so to speak, and I think it would have been interesting to see what it might have done if I'd taken the other, the other fork in the road.
Now you say Harvard and MIT.
Yeah, well, I'm in MIT now.
That's right.
When did you decide to make the move from Harvard to MIT?
And I think I felt very lonely in Harvard.
Yeah, I guess I felt very isolated over there.
And in fact, all my, well, I guess what really happened was I went to, before I went to Harvard, I was working as a kind of adjunct professor at MIT for at least one year.
I think it was one year.
And so I'd known all the people at MIT for a long time, Don Phillips and Joe Charney and Victor Starr.
When I went to, when I went over to Harvard full time, there were only a couple of people there that I really knew.
And all the people in the Cambridge area that I knew were at MIT.
So I began to feel kind of, I began to feel kind of funny.
And I began to question my motives for going to Harvard.
To what degree it was snobbish and things like that.
to which a large extent it is.
It's a game which is played, I think, quite a lot.
Everybody tells each other how good they are.
It gets pretty clawing after a while.
So, anyway, it seemed kind of funny to be over there with all my real contacts and friends for quite a few years, eight years or so, over at MIT.
And so, you know, I didn't...
And it wasn't a very hard decision for me, which I think was really a better thing for me to do.
It's a very business-like, sensible, realistic place.

And in the early days I was first there, I had quite a bit of support from the Draper Laboratory, which was connected with MIT at that time, which helped some graduate students through some instrumental and observational kind of programs.
There was no counterpart to that at that time.
I don't remember how many, but probably five or six graduate students who were profited very much by the fact that they were able to do this.
It was a supporting group.
They were especially technical.
They helped people build things and design things.
Otherwise, we probably couldn't have done it.
That kind of function, I think, now is somewhat diminished at MIT on account of the fact that MIT divested itself of the Draybill Laboratory as a result of student unrest.
And so later students now don't have that quite the same opportunity they had before.
And also, but we still have some kind of coordination.
Carl, why don't you?
but on a more, less on a student basis, more on a project basis.
In other words, the people at the Draper Laboratory aren't helping individual students with individual projects.
It's a big project, and students can get some kind of work done, but their primary interest in the project is not to see a student, which it was before they were domestic.
They still help students a lot, but not on an individual basis.
Do you remember when you accepted your first student to work with you?
Oh, yeah.
I guess it was before I went to Harvard.
I think it was in 1957, or perhaps that's when it was.
I think it was somebody before that, but I think it was Robinson.
And William Malkus and I sort of joined in, except in the summer he came down as a summer student.
At the time we thought he was very dumb and slow.
We just didn't understand why he took so long to anything to sink in.
But he was just being very thorough.
And we talked around for a long time.
It seemed to be very hard to get him started.
And he took both, the two brothers, and did a nice thing.
He wrote a good thesis.

And basically, he was pretty well trained in mathematics, so that he had some nice ideas about similarity solutions and so forth that we never heard about, to apply to trying to develop a theory of the thermocline.
I think that paper was published in 1959, but he started working on it in 1957.
I'm really quite surprised that we kept upgrading our assessment of him all the time.
He came down to us all because he took a kind of descriptive lecture course with Islam.
And Islam brought him down, and when he got down here, Islam didn't know what to do with him.
And so he just sort of shoved them all up in our direction.
We weren't used to the idea of having Stewie, so here we had this guy who was supposed to try to do something.
And as we talked, we didn't seem to know anything, and we didn't think he was going to do anything.
He was going to be a pest, but he turned out quite differently.
In a few weeks, he began the show.
He was asking intelligent questions.
We weren't experienced enough to know that Stewie was off to turn out and start off that way.
But you didn't have many students come into Woods Hole?
Well, I guess not the people who were there full-time.
If you were in the middle 50s, if you were a professor of physics at
Do you think that
I don't want to use the word intellectual climate, because that's not what I mean.
When you talk about Harvard, you were talking about what you wanted the intellectual climate to be.
But do you think the service to an institution, the interchange between students and faculty improve an institution?
Or do you prefer to be at an institution which is simply a research institution?
I think the answer is yes to both of them.
I think the
I think there's no question that professionally oriented students have the energy and imagination to pursue ideas beyond what established people are willing to do.
Partly it's energy, partly it's because they know the techniques, and partly it's just because
But the, so there ought to be, it's very important for the students to be in a place like this.
On the other hand, the notion of graphic institution, I haven't been talking in its whole life now, it's been a few, not a minute.
The notion of graphic institution has a, seems to me, has a primary responsibility
to do research field work at sea.
And that universities have students, universities have computing machines.
Some universities have instrument shops and things like that, engineering type ones have.
But the peculiar thing about an oceanographic institution is the fact that it has
ships or vehicles which can transport people out to the ocean and make measurements, and also technical support groups that are able to, like, one thing, are capable of putting more in the balance.
So the ability to get measurements at sea seems to me to be the first priority of an oceanographic research institution, whereas a university
seems to have its first priority in education, not scholarly research.
Sometimes at MIT, people start saying, wouldn't it be a nice place if we didn't have any students?
And they're thinking about how they'd rather do research than do teaching or supervision of PhDs.
But that doesn't make much sense in the university.
One can see that that's not the top priority.
You try to have a very strong research program because you feel that that's a necessary vehicle to educate people at a graduate level.
It's like a medical school has to be associated with a hospital.
But the priority of the medical school would be to teach doctors even if they weren't allowed in the hospitals.
And the priority of a research institution like this, a lot of it, to make measurements at sea, even though students were banned to come here because we all had some communicable disease.
And so, unfortunately, we know we don't have to.
It isn't black and white matter.
We don't have to make those black and white choices.
I was thinking more, though, in the sort of change in the nature of Woods Hole from, although it's still and always will remain primarily a research institution.
Well, I don't know that, yes it is, I think.
I don't think that the impact of students on Woods Hole has been, I don't know how to assess it.
There are students everywhere.
I have a feeling that if there weren't an educational program in Woods Hole with a dean and so on, there would still be students here in the summertime.
And around.
And the main difference would be that Woods Hole wouldn't have its name on the degree.
But I think students would... Woods Hole would certainly get the credit because it would be obvious that the students had done their work and so it wouldn't matter whose name was on the diploma.
I think...

I think at Woods Hole, for example, as far as I know, even now, there's no way that you can tell when you talk to someone at the institution or look at the institution annual report who's actually teaching and who's not.
There's no clear distinction between
The large majority of people in the institution who don't teach in the ones who do at the university, it's very clear.
Here it's not, and I think probably it's a good idea.
The number of people who actually give courses here is quite small compared to the total number of people at the institution.
I think in only one term.
Physical oceanography, there are three or four courses on it.
Maybe that's the most.
Maybe two or three in the physical oceanography department.
There must be several hundred people in the department.
So I don't know, maybe 9 or 15 graduate students.
They don't saturate them.
And the absence of students had nothing to do with your transfer to Harvard and MIT?
Well, it might have at one time.
I think perhaps I was attracted to MIT.
Once minds do change, people do change over time.
When you began to rather narrow, if I may use that word, your career into your specialty, was it deliberate?
Or did you just seem to more and more of your energy

I think it's, I think that it's basically, as all the different, as all the different parts of the subject become professionalized, each one becomes more intricate and there is a growing body of knowledge and you,
You can't really, at least I can't, keep track of all the different developments.
So what you have to do is to say, either you're going to... Well, maybe the right thing to say is that maybe one
It only seems so.
It's narrowing down a little bit.
Maybe it's just that the field is expanding and that you, it all depends, your reference point, if you, if you, if you, it's a question of some kind of relativity, I suppose.
Either you're getting smaller or the field is getting bigger, but maybe both are happening.
Or maybe, you know, you just don't have, maybe on some scale,
I would say chances are that people don't change much in size, but the field grows.
Probably bigger, probably the most reasonable judgment.
So I think it's probably just a question of the field becoming more and more professionalized.
If a person like myself, I think, tries to
tries to look for new things all the time.
Suppose you were a kind of a hacker carpenter.
You might only do the roughing in work on houses, might you?
And when it came to finishing them up and making them look nice and so forth like that, the real good cabinet makers and so forth would have to come along to the job.
Well, that means that the roughing in contractors don't stand any more job for very long.
They have to look around for new houses that are being built.
So I sort of feel a little bit like a roughing carpenter.

I feel maybe I've done some roughing on a field, and when that field begins to grow and become one where certain kinds of skill and care and so forth are required, I'm not really equipped to be able to handle it.
Well then, you know, I sort of have to give up on that house and try something else.
Maybe that's the model of it.
I don't know what kind.
I think that's probably very, very, it's a little odd.
So, that's what happens.
It does put the,
It does put quite a little bit of burden, it seems to me, on the government.
It's got to kind of look around all the time and find people who want to build houses.
The other guys haven't got such a bad time because the houses are already going to start and people want to finish them.
But it's just the way my life has been, I'm afraid.
Comments on your early colleagues here at Woods Hole?
Whom do you remember about what they were doing, particularly favorably or unfavorably?
Oh, I think I've learned a great deal from many people here.
Ewing gave me the opportunity to go to taste what small boat work like was at sea in the wintertime.
Spine gave me an opportunity to learn something about tools and working machine shops, which I think has always been a source of pleasure for me.
Wyman, Jeffrey Wyman, gave me an idea about how to, more than anyone else I guess, how to do
how to build a construct of thought processes, some kind of a, how to put together some ideas.
Woodcock, Al Woodcock gave me a taste, not very natural, it doesn't come too naturally to me, but it gave me a very good taste, I think, of the naturalist's view of the world.
how to find something of interest, and the simplest kind of love that people don't seem to notice.
And if you look around, you can find them.
Woodcock was wonderful that way.
Ray Montgomery.
gave me some kind of a standard of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, scholar-ness, I guess you'd call it.
The kind of scientist who, uh, who, uh, is careful about what he reads and what he writes and, uh, uh, prudes, uh,
some sense of the... gave me some introductions to professionals in meteorology that I wouldn't have had from any of the others.
I met Rossby from... Rossby, I guess, gave me the first indication...
I met Rossby in 1946.
Rossby gave me the first
an indication of how very, how very, how you could learn something from the most vastly simplified theoretical models.
You know, maximum simplification is what I learned, what I think I learned from Rosby.
Of course, I mean, I can't go very beyond maximum simplification.
I can't make things very complicated, so maximum simplification is a very useful thing.
But I think I really learned that, you know, to strip things down from him.
You could learn, certainly, in his simple things, most simple models that we construct.
So I guess I may have left...
I may have left some people out, but I think that brings me up to about, I think it brings me up to around 1954, 1955.
It probably touches the main, main contacts that I had with the group that I think affected me in significant ways.
I guess from that time on, I was probably about 35 or something like that.
Probably not so strongly affected by other people so much in the same kind of way that determines what your career personality is going to be like.
Whom did you ask to read your first paper?
in criticizing?
Fort Wyman, I think.
Probably, probably, you know, I think the first paper I wrote was a terrible paper that I wrote for some New York Academy's meeting with, with Fort Wyman, and
It was kind of an awful paper.
He didn't seem to like it that much.
And then my Cumulus Cloud paper, I guess, 1947, he stimulated to a large extent.
And I guess
I guess Wyman was my main contact.
